snippet.textDisplay: You cooked the ram-don wrong. Refer to the other YouTube videos making ram-don or jjapaguri, as they're called. You're supposed to boil the noodles with the flakes from the flake packets, drain out most of the water, then add both the Neoguri and Chapagetti soup packets and mix. What's the point of adding the Neoguri soup packet while you're boiling the noodles, then draining it out? You're throwing away the flavor from the Neoguri packet. If you're going to represent another culture's noodles, at least get it right. Unsubscribed.
snippet.textOriginal: You cooked the ram-don wrong. Refer to the other YouTube videos making ram-don or jjapaguri, as they're called. You're supposed to boil the noodles with the flakes from the flake packets, drain out most of the water, then add both the Neoguri and Chapagetti soup packets and mix. What's the point of adding the Neoguri soup packet while you're boiling the noodles, then draining it out? You're throwing away the flavor from the Neoguri packet. snippet.textDisplay:
As a Korean American who has lived in Korea for over a decade, i get pissed that Koreans cant spell.
Its not like the Japanese where they actually cant pronounce English words, for some reason Koreans spell “uh” words with “eo”.
So its actually pronounced Nuh-goo-ree with the r in ree in this case very similar to how Spanish speakers pronounce their r’s with a roll.
It is not Neo like Keanu in the gotdamn Matrix.

snippet.textDisplay: I watched other videos of making ramdon and they seemed more authentic, in your video you wasted neoguri spice by removing the water most spice got drained out in the water,  the actual procedure would be to first boil the noodles and the flakes in plain water without adding any spice and removing the excess water then adding both spices into the simmering noodles and adding the meat then sauteing it. This way you will get the actual colour and flavour of jjapaguri.
snippet.textOriginal: I watched other videos of making ramdon and they seemed more authentic, in your video you wasted neoguri spice by removing the water most spice got drained out in the water,  the actual procedure would be to first boil the noodles and the flakes in plain water without adding any spice and removing the excess water then adding both spices into the simmering noodles and adding the meat then sauteing it. This way you will get the actual colour and flavour of jjapaguri.
